| CNBC Software Flaw Worth $1 Million?                               |
|   from the that's-quite-a-bug dept.                                |
|   posted by Zonk on Monday June 11, @03:11 (Software)              |
|   http://games.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/06/11/0428214        |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

Strudelkugel writes "BusinessWeek tells the story of one obsessive fan
who [0]unraveled a software glitch worth one million dollars. Jim Kraber
was a regular CNBC viewer, and when the opportunity arose he took the
'Million Dollar Portfolio Challenge' very seriously. At one point, he was
spending 12 hours a day on the contest, using three computers to trade
1,600 different portfolios in a theoretical stock game. His efforts got
him into the top 20 finalists, but in the last round of trading he
noticed some unusual patterns. 'One trader had a stream of near-perfect
picks, consistently placing huge bets on shares that soared in
after-hours trading. Kraber suspected the trader and perhaps others were
getting help from someone who was changing their picks after the stocks'
increases â€” and he quickly notified CNBC ... Kraber says CNBC rebuffed
him at the time, but now it looks like he may have been right.'"

Discuss this story at:
    http://games.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/06/11/0428214

